{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538080"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:24:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:24:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16126"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16126"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.47,0.13,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107060"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8817"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16126"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89524"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3015"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5905"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29820"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43609"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107060"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with persistent burning pain and allodynia over her left thoracic dermatome. The pain began during a shingles infection three months ago and has not improved. She rates the pain as 7/10 and reports it causes her constant distress and significantly impacts her sleep. She reports that her poor sleep is contributing to increased irritability and low mood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, depression and osteoarthritis. Her regular medications include metformin, perindopril and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is an area of post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation with scarring in the left T6 dermatome. Sensory examination reveals allodynia in the affected area. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oxycodone","Fluoxetine","Amitriptyline","Lignocaine patch","Pregabalin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of post-herpetic neuralgia (PHN), which is defined as pain persisting for more than three months following acute \u003Cem\u003EVaricella zoster\u003C/em\u003E virus reactivation. The condition typically presents with burning pain and allodynia in the affected dermatome. The risk of developing PHN increases significantly with age, with up to 50% of patients over 70 years developing persistent pain after shingles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmitriptyline\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial treatment for PHN. Tricyclic antidepressants have demonstrated superior efficacy in multiple randomised controlled trials, with a number needed to treat of 3.2 for significant pain relief. The typical starting dose is 10-25 mg at night, gradually titrated according to response and tolerability. Importantly, amitriptyline offers dual benefits in this patient by addressing both neuropathic pain and the mood disturbance/sleep disruption she is experiencing. Given her history of depression and current irritability and low mood related to poor sleep, amitriptyline\u0027s antidepressant effects provide an additional potential benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPregabalin\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective treatment for PHN and is also considered first-line. However, while it would address the neuropathic pain component, it would not specifically target the mood and sleep disturbances that this patient is experiencing. Additionally, it may cause significant sedation and dizziness, particularly in elderly patients, which could increase fall risk. In this specific case, amitriptyline is more appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluoxetine\u003C/strong\u003E is a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) that is not indicated for the treatment of neuropathic pain conditions such as PHN. While it may help with depression, it lacks the analgesic properties needed to address the patient\u0027s primary complaint of neuropathic pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELignocaine patches\u003C/strong\u003E provide localised pain relief and can be useful as adjunct therapy or in mild cases. However, given this patient\u0027s significant pain (7/10) and the need for coverage while sleeping, lignocaine patches alone are unlikely to provide adequate benefit as they can only be worn for 12 hours per day, followed by a patch-free interval. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxycodone\u003C/strong\u003E and other opioids should be avoided as first-line therapy for PHN due to their significant side effect profile, risk of falls in elderly patients, and potential for dependence. They may have a limited role in severe cases that have failed other treatments, but only as part of a comprehensive pain management strategy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tricyclic antidepressants may be used to treat post-herpetic neuralgia.","Post-herpetic neuralgia is defined as pain persisting more than 3 months after acute herpes zoster infection.","The risk of post-herpetic neuralgia increases significantly with age, particularly in those over 70 years."],"references":["G\u00f3nima Valero E, Mendoza WA, Sarmiento DA, Amaya S. Analgesic treatment approach for postherpetic neuralgia: a narrative review. Journal of Pain \u0026 Palliative Care Pharmacotherapy. 2023 Apr 3;37(2):184-93. Available online at ; https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/15360288.2023.2174632","Finnerup NB, Attal N, Haroutounian S, McNicol E, Baron R, Dworkin RH, Gilron I, Haanp\u00e4\u00e4 M, Hansson P, Jensen TS, Kamerman PR, Lund K, Moore A, Raja SN, Rice AS, Rowbotham M, Sena E, Siddall P, Smith BH, Wallace M. Pharmacotherapy for neuropathic pain in adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Lancet Neurol. 2015 Feb;14(2):162-73. doi: 10.1016/S1474-4422(14)70251-0. Epub 2015 Jan 7. PMID: 25575710; PMCID: PMC4493167. Available online at ; https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25575710/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89524"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16126"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89524"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T22:16:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T18:34:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8817"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107060"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHead